ladders.explanation:
This is the core computational component of the full solution. We need both the divisors of n and their φ values efficiently. The intuition: divisors of n can be found in O(√n) by checking up to √n. For each divisor d, φ(d) can be computed using its prime factors. Since all divisors share factors from n's prime factorization, we can factorize n once and use it to compute φ(d) quickly.

Algorithm: 1) Factorize n to get prime factors with exponents. Store as dictionary {p: exp}. 2) Generate all divisors using recursive combination of prime factors. For each divisor d, compute φ(d) = d * Π_{p|d} (1 - 1/p). Since we know the prime factors of d (subset of n's factors), we can compute this directly.

Alternative approach: Generate divisors by iterating i=1 to √n, for each i dividing n, add i and n/i. Then for each divisor d, compute φ(d) by factoring d separately (less efficient but simpler).

Time: O(√n) for divisor generation, O(√d) for φ computation per divisor if done separately, but overall still O(√n) since number of divisors is O(√n). Space: O(√n) to store divisors.

Connection to L0: This provides the Σ d*φ(d) term needed in the main formula.

Common mistakes: Not handling duplicate divisors when n is perfect square (i = n/i), incorrect φ(1) computation, integer division issues in φ formula.

Real code pattern:
def get_divisors_and_phi(n):
    divisors = []
    phi_vals = {}
    # Generate divisors
    for i in range(1, int(sqrt(n))+1):
        if n % i == 0:
            divisors.append(i)
            if i != n//i:
                divisors.append(n//i)
    # Compute φ for each divisor
    for d in divisors:
        phi = d
        temp = d
        for p in range(2, int(sqrt(temp))+1):
            if temp % p == 0:
                while temp % p == 0:
                    temp //= p
                phi -= phi // p
        if temp > 1:
            phi -= phi // temp
        phi_vals[d] = phi
    return divisors, phi_vals
